    "narrative": "LawDog\u2019s lineup for April 25th is anchored by **Cal Raleigh** (71.30) and **Will Smith** (70.62), our two most efficient starts today. **Cal Raleigh** benefits significantly from a favorable matchup against Matthew Liberatore, with his projected efficiency bolstered by an 8% boost for holding the #2 spot in the order and a 6% platoon advantage. Similarly, **Will Smith** draws a strong scoring profile against Colin Rea, aided by wind conditions providing a 5% boost to his base output. While **Geraldo Perdomo** (68.05) remains a high-floor play due to his leadoff role and the exploitable 5.26 xERA of Germ\u00e1n M\u00e1rquez, he carries a 36% rain risk that necessitates close monitoring as the day progresses.\n\nStrategic platoon and park factors heavily influenced the lower half of the starting roster. **Bryson Stott** (66.12) is a priority start, leveraging a 13% dynamic platoon boost against Bryce Elder, while **Taylor Ward** (59.46) overcomes a tough matchup against Crochet by utilizing a massive 16% park factor advantage, making him a high-reward play despite the elite opposition. The most difficult decision on the bench involved **Gleyber Torres** (50.43); while he offers a strong pedigree, his efficiency was suppressed by a negative 13% platoon adjustment against Brady Singer, ultimately causing him to lose out to **Wenceel Perez** (44.34) and the overall optimizer priority. **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** (59.41) remains in the lineup despite a poor BvP history against Kevin Gausman, as his base projection remains high enough to warrant a start even with the slight regression in his scoring components. \n\nMonitor the lineup confirmations for **Jonathan Aranda** and **Gavin Sheets**, as both are currently slated for high-leverage spots despite the 36% rain risk impacting **Gavin Sheets**. We are keeping **Yainer Diaz** and **Drew Gilbert** on the bench as secondary pivots, but their current scoring profiles do not supersede the established platoon advantages of our active starters. Ensure that the game caps are managed efficiently, particularly for our fringe outfielders, as we navigate this dense slate.",
